element_texts.text:
Dear Brother Issac
I have just returned from Hampden, whither we felt obliged to go to see about our girl, as soon as we found Ellen was really going to leave us Thursday-was much disappointed to find you gone - you had only been gone ten minutes, Ellen said - and you forgot your little girl, I was sure of seeing you again I had ever so many things to say. 
It is well that you did go Tuesday isn't it? Now won't it be so bad going that we can't go to Milo?
Ellen left us for good yesterday p.m., expecting to start for Minn. today, but I hardly think the boats got in yesterday. The poor girl cried sadly. You should have seen her hold Perci away & look in his face as if she

never meant to forget him, then hold his hands in both of hers and look at him again, without hardly speaking at all.  It seemed to distress her that he wouldn't feel bad about her going.  He would say over after her "Nellens going away -never, never see Perci any more", but he didn't feel it as she wanted him to. We shall never see her like again in many aspects- I couldn't help crying myself- From all accounts, we are likely to be fortunate in the next girl- I suppose she cannot come till next week, Little Charlotte Chalmers is staying with me a few days - she is nicely helpful & very pleasant. I gave Perci catnip tea yesterday & I cut his gums in eight places without his making a word of objection  Three great double teeth just ready to come through & very much swollen - He slept much more quietly last night - I felt so anxious

Lucy
July 6 1855
Bangor July 6 1855
Mine dear Brother
Your most acceptable letter of June 29 was rec'd last night. It is now quarter past eight P.M. Samuel is at the store as usual, little P.P. in his crib asleep, Lizzie eating pea-nuts on the lounge & Ellen in the kitchen knitting. I have been in the garden watering and tending lime trees?. I do great business there, I can assure you. I wrote you latterly directing to Sn Irwin, telling you all about the garden and how the labor of your hands is prospering, but I think it doubtful if you got the letter before leaving.
I am quite a husbandman these days and my out door labors are decidedly beneficial to me. I have thoroughly wed my posy patch, so there is hard by a weed to be seen in the paths or

or elsewhere, have transplanted and arranged nicely, and besides have almost wholly weeded the beds & parsnips, tended the vines to keep away the bugs, digged about the tomatoes & watered all things most faithfully- I like to stay out there so well that I forget to come in when I am tired frequently. The Okra is doing finely and two plants of Mr.s Page unclear "Martanns" are up & looking well. Mr. Moran has been here and bred? the garden fixed gravel walks unclear the little rose bushes down by the fence are prospering & the Praire rose looking beautifully, I have ripped off half the buds for the benefit of the bush. I want you here to look at things with one, though doubtless you see many things every day better worth looking at than anything here. Samuel has been to Searsport three times this week to see about his lumber. He has

many rafts of boards taken down there and Juliet use to season? Thinking there may be a rake for their next winter when it would be different to get them from here. This lumber business, as it is at present, is a sad perplexity. I presume you have heard from Nettie all about Percie's illness at Milo & how I came home with him sooner than I intended. He was quite sick two or three days after I got back- discharged a good deal of blood- but I think that & the fir? all occasioned by eating three beans swallowed without sufficient chewing, as he passed one almost whole two days after eating it. He seems a little too much relaxed all the time & I am obliged to be constantly careful in regard to his diet, otherwise he is well now. Eliab thinks of going to Milo for Maria next Thursday. I suppose they have all gone to Brownville now. I guess I shall let Livvie go up

and come back with him - just to stay one or two nights. Samuel was going to Hampden? on business this AM so I rode down to Mr Crosly so they hear about once a week from William and Rufus. Their address is Atchison, Kansas Territory. They have bought a claim, built a house and store, got their spring crops inward when William wrote last, he was just going to St. Louis to buy goods, they seem to be doing well, but their parents are intensely anxious about them, as is very natural. William is ready to leave & intending to do so I believe so soon as engineering business can be obtained. They are only ten miles from Sarah Parker in Misouri, I have just written to Theo's wife, so I don't know as I have any message to send to the Minn, brethren?, but I wish you would pick up some nice little curiosities now & then in your travels.
